so this excercise is a bit different, we must analyze how the heap is being build, how each instruction change it and how is getting stacked

when we call a malloc in heap memory looks like this

metadata<-----this metadat is 8 bytes long
userdata<-----here is the pointer that the malloc returns

that is a chunk, so when we are stacking chunks it would look like this

metadatac1<-----this metadat is 8 bytes long
userdatac1<-----here is the pointer that the malloc returns
metadatac2<-----this metadat is 8 bytes long
userdatac2<-----here is the pointer that the malloc returns
metadatac3<-----this metadat is 8 bytes long
userdatac3<-----here is the pointer that the malloc returns

so in this case we are ollocating first 64 bytes of user data
then we are alocating again 4 for the pointer adress

so from where we are to the pointer adress there is 64 bytes of user data, 8 bytes of metadata of the second chunk, and 4 bytes of the user data of the second chunk where the m function adress is held, we must write this, so lets get the n adress to replace the m with the n

